                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d571">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/10209</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-10T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 10, 1916, 5 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3913. Department’s 3872.<note n="1" xml:id="d571fn1">Not printed.</note> Consul,
                    Trinidad, telegraphs American S. S. <hi rend="italic">Pathfinder</hi> delayed
                    there at cost $1,500 daily while awaiting permit from London for bunker coal.
                    Bring matter to attention Foreign Office in connection with similar cases and
                    inquire if it is established practice of British Government to accord to
                    American vessels treatment this character which has in several instances
                    resulted in serious loss to vessels. Request prompt reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
